<taxonomicName id="4C694D67FFD1C8083EEEE27C6F4D9D0F" authority="(Linnaeus, 1767)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1767" box="[174,564,1295,1322]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Catocala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nupta">
<emphasis id="B91DEAF6FFD1C8083EEEE27C6C109D0F" bold="true" box="[174,361,1295,1322]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">Catocala nupta</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1767)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EA3E23369A99D7C" blockId="5.[174,1232,1343,1402]" box="[227,1232,1343,1370]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical, flattened (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083CBEE24C6E379D7F" box="[766,846,1343,1370]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,184,1656]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1233,184,1682]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 25–28 — Catocala elocata; 29, 30 — Catocala nupta. Scale bars: 25, 26, 29, 30 — 100 µm; 27, 28 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453450/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 29</figureCitation>
), height 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD1C8083DF9E24C69219D7F" box="[953,1112,1343,1370]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.25" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" unit="mm" value="0.625" valueMax="0.75" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.75 mm</quantity>
, diameter
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD1C8083EEEE22C6F5F9DC0" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EEEE22C6F9F9D5F" blockId="5.[174,1232,1343,1402]" box="[174,742,1375,1402]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD1C8083EEEE22C6C409D5F" box="[174,313,1375,1402]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.1">1.1–1.2 mm</quantity>
(n = 2). Chorion white, transparent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EA3E2F96F5F9DC0" blockId="5.[174,1233,1418,1509]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
R e m a r k. The sculpture similar to previous species, but more distinct. Longitudinal ridges sharply expressed, wider and elevated than transwerse ridges. Transwerse ridges less wavy than in 
<emphasis id="B91DEAF6FFD1C8083F0BE2B96CC79DC1" box="[331,446,1482,1508]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
С. 
<taxonomicName id="4C694D67FFD1C8083F2CE2B96CC79DC1" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Esper" baseAuthorityYear="1787" box="[364,446,1482,1508]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Catocala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elocata">elocata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083F8CE2B96F609DC0" box="[460,537,1482,1509]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,184,1656]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1233,184,1682]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 25–28 — Catocala elocata; 29, 30 — Catocala nupta. Scale bars: 25, 26, 29, 30 — 100 µm; 27, 28 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453450/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 30</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
